==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{term|dismal|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|(li) dis mals||(the) bad days|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|diēs||day}} {{term|mālī||bad|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|[ˈdɪzməɫ]|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Disappointingly [[inadequate]].
#: {{ux|en|He received a '''dismal''' compensation.}}
#* {{quote-news|year=2012|date=April 22|author=Sam Sheringham|work=BBC Sport
|title=[http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17718147 Liverpool 0-1 West Brom]
|passage=Liverpool's efforts thereafter had an air of desperation as their '''dismal''' 2012 league form continued.}}
# [[gloomy|Gloomy]] and [[bleak]].
#:  {{ux|en|The storm made for a '''dismal''' weekend}}
# [[depressing|Depressing]].
#:  {{ux|en|She was lost in '''dismal''' thoughts of despair}}
#*{{quote-book|year=1913|author={{w|Joseph C. Lincoln}}|chapter=12
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5535161W Mr. Pratt's Patients]
|passage=So, after a spell, he decided to make the best of it and shoved us into the front parlor. 'Twas a '''dismal''' sort of place, with hair wreaths, and wax fruit, and tin lambrekins, and land knows what all. It looked like a tomb and smelt pretty nigh as musty and dead-and-gone.}}

====Usage notes====
* Nouns to which "dismal" is often applied: failure, performance, state, record, place, result, scene, season, year, economy, future, fate, weather, news, condition, history.

